segments.text: This is an interview with Craig Champion by Susan Turgeon on November 26, 1988, at Craig Champion's home in Grosbeck, Texas, concerning the Vietnam War.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge about the war, I'm going to donate this type to the Texas A&M oral history collection in the university archives.
Is that all right with you?
Yes.
Were you drafted or did you enlist?
Volunteer.
Volunteer.
Out of high school, or how old were you then?
I was 19.
Did you have any thoughts?
I mean, did you really know what was going on over there, or what we were fighting for?
Not really.
In high school, I don't think that nobody really gave Vietnam a thought.
And right out of high school, I went to Prairie Game College.
Right out of school, I went to summer school.
And still haven't given the first thought.
Maybe it crossed my mind some, but that's a long one.
We have everybody.
Talked about, in the year 66, year after, talked about joining the Marine Corps.
But he might have been going on the police system.
But I don't think he could pass the pistol, so I just put him on the police.
Got a letter from the draft board.
So I just went on down to the barbecue and kind of kicked it up.
Really didn't know what was going on until you got in the Army and then they let you know what the question was.
Did they tell you about the politics and everything?
I mean, did you know what you were fighting for while you were there?
No, it was about the only thing the Army basic training would tell you.
It was communism.
Nothing in detail.
and how we got over there and why we went over there.
Did they train you militarily adequately for when you got there for the kind of war that it was?
The training, was it appropriate because it was a guerrilla war?
Well, it's kind of hard to train for that really.
I guess we went through the standard basic training.
Uh, AIT, I was a combat medic.
I went through a medical training for eight months before I went over.
And, uh, I was just working in the hospital.
And I dealt with a lot of, uh, wounded Vietnam boys coming back from the Iranian farm.
And, uh, of course, I, I got, uh, pretty well informed on what was going over, you know, before I got there.
But as far as what kind of action he was going to see when he got over there, it depended on where they sent you.
What's it called?
The Highlands, you know, the Delta, Acon.
I got sent to the Acon Delta.
You didn't see much action with what's called a regular army, mostly up north until 10.
Most of our combat time was spent fighting snipers.
It kind of reminded me of the cowboy and Indian day, you know, the cowboy riding through and Indians waiting on them as they stopped to pick them up.
And putting up the booty traps.
So it was always the unexpected you had to be ready for.
Where were you stationed over there?
Base camp was a place called Dome Town.
And when I got there, they attached me to what's called a mobile riverine force.
And they put us on a ship that was anchored in the Mekong Harbor Bay.
And they had what's called ATCs on personnel carriers and Navy around.
And they'd load us up on those grassroots early in the morning before daybreak.
And we grew up in these clouds.

and then they'd turn in the beach and we had to unload straight into the jungle and we may walk anywhere from a day to two weeks before we came back before helicopters came in and picked us up but we came back around to the river so when we went out you really didn't know how long we were going to be out
When you went out there, what was your mission?
Just to find Cypress, or?
They had titles called Search and Destroy, Ambush Patrol, and just Recon.
Most of them were just Search and Destroy missions.
Maybe get a tip from one of the civilians, whatever.
That's it.
Maybe a bunker full of guns or grenades or whatever in this village.
If it looked like it was D.C. controlled, the way you could tell that was by the amount of rice they had stored in the underground tunnels that they built in the bunkers inside the hoochies.

You can go down in those things and if they were pretty well fortified, lots of blankets and first aid equipment, you knew it was probably at least easy to get behind the camp and build those places up and come and get down.
A lot of times you wouldn't get the right one until, you know, a lot of people suck at being civilian and I'm just part of being in a war area.
How did the people at Church of the Reign meet people that you encountered?
About as well as you treat them.
If you treated them like human beings, they liked the GI.
Of course, there's always ones that, you know, the police would like to push them around.
And I've always thought that
Somebody pushed one around, and they got word to the Fiat car.
And the smart people, the real smart people, said they could pick him out.
The sniper could pick him out and be the first one to go down.
I couldn't prove that, but I've seen it happen.
A guy that just, let's say a bully may steal a coat or something, a coat leg, an old thing that had been stolen.
little baskets on the pole and they'd run down to the paddy bikes.
Sometimes they'd run right up to you in a firefight.
Of course, we wouldn't be following them.
And I'd try to sell you a coat.
And somebody, you know, steal a little old lady's coat or something like that.
That's an explanation of how they did it a couple months ago.
uh, ironic or whatever, but I've always thought that they had a lot of ties with the Viet Cong.
You know, uh, they're sons, cousins or whatever, you know.
And, uh, but they, uh, the Viet Cong, you know, they were, uh, mostly civilians in the daytime, plowing or whatever, and then, uh, they'd either drop a plow to get to AK-47 or,
during the daytime or most times at night times.
Did you fight any with Arlen, please?
Yeah, yeah.
What kind of fighters were those?
I've heard we've had people come and talk to us and we've had discrepancies report.
They're another group.
I think a lot of it's too dependent on what outfit and who trained them.
A good trained orbit outfit I've seen by a great, great majority of them, in my opinion.
Just cracked a little bit.
They'd wear their little silk headscarves, or blue scarves, or green scarves, whatever outfit they were with.
Didn't see a lot of them actually.
You think we should have given them more responsibility?
worked more closely with them and trained them into their job instead of, it seemed like we went over there and we took care of everything and they were just kind of on the side.
Yeah, that's basically the way it was.
I don't even know, I don't think that we would have given them any more authority whether they would have handled the situation.
It would have been a bigger mess.
If Washington would have just let the army do their job over there, it would have been over a hundred times better.
You think the war could have been won if it had been fought differently?
Sure.
A lot of people got wealthy back here.
And that's the expense of a lot of young men.
But I never gave that much thought while I was over there.
That was only after I got back and, you know, years later.
It seems like just in the past few years that the Vietnam Air experience, you know, is coming back.
And the movies, you know, you read a lot about it and you can't pick up the paper.
I'm just now kind of digging into the heart of it.
But at that time in 68,
I didn't care less about politics.
I went over because I was, you know, for my country.
As corny as it seems, that's why I was there.
And I was ready to give everything I had.
Do you think the government betrayed you now that you know that they weren't doing everything they could and you were over there trying to give it your all?
I never thought of it as betraying me, but I guess you could look at it like that.
Of course, I don't hold many grudges with any of them, because I don't even know them.
And I often thought that it was all to do over again, though I don't know how would I have done it.
I'm not so sure I would.
I'm not so sure I would leave.
It was just too costly.
They're alive.
The money is left.
It's alive.
Did you have buddies that didn't come back that were killed over there?
Yeah, that's it.
Of course, you got to pay a lot of money in the medics.
Yeah.
Yeah, I was just about 12, 100% of the time.
I had a lot of them.
A couple wounded, enough to come back.
I lost one today where they're at .
I don't know.
I don't know.
I know some of them are fine.
I know one was paralyzed and was shot in the spine.
I'm also one that's definitely on the back.
You haven't seen any of them since you went in there?
The only contact I've made was with my best friend.
He was blown up by a claymore monster.
He was from El Campo.
And he was at the hospital, San Antonio, about a year.
I had about three months left in the country when he was killed.
I wrote his fiancee and his mom and dad, and they got back in contact with me, and we corresponded.
And when I got back, I drove to San Antonio to stay in contact with him.
He was a pretty big old boy and he messed up pretty good and lost an eye and got a steel plate in his head and the rest of it kind of looks like hamburgers.
He came through it pretty well.
He got married and got his degree in oceanography.
I hadn't heard from him in five or six years.
So as far as I know, he's the one that scarred that.
The news coverage that was covered by TV, do you think a lot of that was accurate?
that was portrayed back over here.
Did you ever work with a news team?
Yeah, we had a news week that followed us for about 60 days.
And on this educational channel, when they had this Vietnam stuff going on, I'm not real sure, but I think I saw a shot.
Captions of who it was, a lot of food, just tapes and bits and pieces from a lot of correspondence.
Well, yeah, a lot of it had to be because it was live.
The camera was, you know, they had it there rolling.
You think that should have been shown back over here?
I don't know.
I know my mom and dad, they kept up with us pretty close.

Dad moved and went out and bought a huge, wild Vietnam map, and I'd write a letter and tell him, you know, where we were going on this next operation, or where we'd been, and what we were doing before then.
He'd get out, and I noticed he had it all marked on the map.
It was about every place that I drove and told him where we'd been on the population, so he kept up with me.
I don't know.
I think maybe it helped them to...
I think in the back of their mind, they really knew what was going on in there.
I think maybe the TV coverage kind of helped them.
I'd want to know what my son was.
There was a lot, maybe a lot of school, you know, battle on the TV.
Were you out of one of your tears, did you?
What's your opinion about that?

Do you think that they should have been longer tours or do you think that by the time you got over there, well, we've been told that you got over there and you had like, by the time you got out in the field, you had like six months just to get out in the field because you went to Vietnam and then you got your orders and you went to Saigon for a while and then you got shipped out.
Do you think you were there long enough to have an impact for just one year?

Or do you think it should have been... Because I said, people I've talked to said that, like, by the time you have, like, three months left, well, you're not worried about anything but getting back alive, mainly.
You know, that you're just, you're ready to go home.
And you're not so much concerned about fighting, you're just really worried about keeping yourself alive.
Yeah.
What they call getting sharp.
And where it will last, I guess, 90 days.
I mean...
It kind of weighs on your mind.
You don't want to blow it.
This late in the game, you want to get out of it.
But I've always felt like that the more careful you try to be when you get shortest window, you're going to mess up.
I don't know.
I think I lived the last day the same as I lived the first day.
I came close a lot of times.
Black Jackets stopped a lot of them.
and fragments, a lot of bullets close by when it reached right off the top of the field pocket, but never shed a drop of blood.
It was bleached by an enemy.
And I think it's just, you can't let it, you can't think about it, you can't let it bother you.
You've just got to take it.
take your destiny, whatever it's going to be, whatever it's going to be.
Of course, that's not saying to be a hero, either.
You can be a hero, but be smart.
Somebody just jumping up and running into an area, he doesn't know where he's going.
He probably won't come out.
A smart way to do it and a dumb way to do it.
As far as the time over there, I don't know.
That place, a year is about all I think an average villa can take in certain areas.
It was a whole different conflict.
I call it a war.
Anytime bullets are fired, I call it a war.
That kicks me off when I read the amount of time for it.
I know it wasn't declared, but they say it was a war, and I always did it.
But that kite over there with the weather conditions, the elements, and the age of the GI over there, I think a year.
That's about all they need to be able to do.
And it's all what you want to make of it.
Then the ones that are really into it and always volunteer for another tour do a lot of it.
You can even volunteer for an extra three or four years in the Army on and out.
I drafted for two years.
And he just can't take it over there.
He melts out.
They volunteered for the next two or three or four years of Army life, and they made a big mistake.
I'm going to have to comment on that.
But I can hear this thing.
You know, it's a choice.
I've often wondered how, you know, World War II, that you went to the war they were with or you got in or whatever, where you killed and they came back.
I just don't know.
I think it would have been a lot worse.
A lot of GIs over there took off anyway.
In my own mind, a lot of these missions and actions, it never hurt them.
I'm probably alive and well there somewhere right now.
It just took off.
It wouldn't.
It was just, you know, it's what's been made.
Were you involved with the Winning the Hearts of Minded People program?
I think they had.
But you were, you tried to be the Vietnamese friend who
when you went into the village?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, I never, uh, I never missed seeing any of the villagers.
Uh, they liked me anyway because I was boxing about too many.
Every one of them wanted a band-aid.
Uh, the kids and the mommasides all come to you for those days and sit, um, and get half an aspirin and everything's all right.
Put a band-aid on.
Some of them did.
and had no scars, infected scars, no medication.
And you could really befriend them, at least in that way.
You think that whole idea was even possible, really, though?
With, I guess, the bad apples in your back?
It was very difficult.
You could go into, say, a village,

uh you may leave that village and uh the old chief in the village he may say you know yeah as americans told you all right they were treated very even left their sea rashes whatever and then you walk out of the village and there's an old water buffalo and there's an old pot shot and you'll see what a m79 grenade launcher will do to a water buffalo and then you just go on
Well, you've blown everything you've accomplished in that business, but it's hard to do because you're the ones that care less.
How do things change for you at the Tech?
Are they different for you?
Yeah.
It seems like the actual...
The resistance that you met when you went out in the fields was like my own life.
It was more just lots of walking, old boots and tracks.
Not many knew it was being, you know, built.
You can tell when one's been there, you don't know how much it's been built, how long it's been there.
You've been there for 10 years, just firing each day.
The Mac division, who I was with, we pretty well pushed the car, I say, pushed them out.
Maybe we didn't.
They just slowly quit fighting as much.
And I say we didn't.
We never did it like that much.
I don't know if we did or not.
I know after it was over with, I highly underestimated them.
It was amazing, I think.
A lot more than we could do with what we would have had to get in the same situation right now.
They could take anything and make a person out of it.
I don't think they were that brave as fighters.
I think that they would get a trickier hit run and make them take it.
take a bamboo sheet and make a mortar out of it.
That kind of thing.
It's a very beautiful thing.
If anybody left behind, they could take it.
What are the awards you're supposed to get from the Vietnamese government?
What?
That was their country's medal, their country's medal.
I think it's their country's highest medal.
In the United States, I think, probably equivalent to our DSC, but I don't know.
The Congressional is our highest medal, so I don't know what it is.
When did that, what led to that?
We were airlifted in, into an LZ, we got off the choppers.
We hadn't gone far, maybe 100 yards.
We were in the middle of a rice paddy in the woodland, maybe another 100 yards south.
We were strung out, I guess, as far as the point, being almost within 40 yards of the woodland and as far back as a couple hundred yards.
Sniper's in the woodland over there.
and probably roughly 12, if it wasn't 6 or 12 times.
And it turned into an all day fire fight.
And it kept us pinned down.
We couldn't move.
We couldn't see them.
The baby boots stuck out like sore thumbs.
The grass got that high.
And there was an old hooch right out in the middle, and that turned into the command post.
And, of course, there were some padded-backs that almost everybody worked on.
Padded-backs, padded-backs, padded-backs.
And, at the point, the machine gun and his ammo barrel were both shot through the head.
They weren't dead.
The radio man made some movement for free, and that radio was back there.
I got to the command post and I said they need a medic to pull in.
I looked up there and it was kind of hard.
It was hot and there was a lot of bullets coming.
It was one of those things where you could just say I can't do it.
That day I found out that I just wasn't made of it.
I was more scared after the go with than going up there.
And that's where I caught a ricochet.
And got up there.
It was a big soldier's off to the high left and they just pointed to the two guys over there.
And in the meantime, we had Air Force.
They were bombing the woodlands while they were gone.
The snipers had nearly come back out of the bunkers while they were gone.
I got a word to them they were both pretty bad.
Trying to patch them.
You just had to get up and kind of do it.
You just had to throw some fire at them, put them back in the bunker, and then put a patch on them, ace band advantage.
So I needed to stay with it.
And because I wasn't the only medic in the outfield out there, just to handle whatever else.
But at that time, those two guys needed a medic there at that time.
So we were right there in front of them.
You know, we were right up with them.
I stayed with them.
And we changed gunfire, made it three hours, and took care of them anyway after that.
Jets finally, I guess they hit the bunkers close enough to where it pushed them on back down.
They disappeared somewhere.
And the choppers came in, took the guys on the choppers, lost one of them.
I don't know.
I don't know.
Later on.
And then we stayed there in the field that night.

do you think the volume was affected as they used to make all those things yeah do you think there were actual targets or you know the methods were reported are they just so in line involved well uh the uh the 111 the airport the passport we called in down in the delta yeah they were
They were accurate enough.
I mean, if we had something dropped to him, we'd come back so close that we'd want to catch some of the stuff.
And we had soldiers, our own men, shrapnel ripped through one of them.
I didn't lose anything.
Arm or leg or part of the face or something like that.
Shrapnel or a bomb.
Maybe they won't see what a bomb looked like when it went off.
But it was close enough.
Late time, and I didn't like that stuff.
Real close in there.
Real close.
Got a bad smell to it, too.
It burns the flesh.
It burns the flesh.
Tell when it's doing its job.
The smell.
I guess that's what I remember the most.
They call it the smell.
But as far as the B-52 rays, the big bombs, I don't think they were just bombing.
I'm sure a lot of bombs didn't get to targets involved in that too.
But as far as the fighter jets, you know, they were looking pretty good, I think.
That's just one spot.
Whatever it was, they were an airstrike for us, but it didn't go out that way.
And they got us out alive.
We couldn't move them, they couldn't move us.
They had us, and they took them out for us to put some heavy stuff on them.
Our artillery got a lot, but it just didn't seem like it had good effect at the time.
How did you feel when you got right here?
Were you tired?
Oh, I don't know.
He sure wasn't a hero, but when he got to California, a lot of them, like the one I talked to, he was on there.
You know, they harassed him.
I wouldn't say harassed him.
You know, they were at the airport.
All kinds of stuff.
I didn't pay much attention to him.
But I processed out in Oakland, California, on the flight from Oakland.
But Dallas loved Phil.
In fact, a guy went and placed a plane with a technician who got out of the fourth division at the same time.
He rode on the same plane from California.
Uh, wouldn't stewardages, civilian people on the plane, they would hate him, no question.
I just kind of laid around the house for the first week, and the first thing I did when
Did your friends and people that knew you then over there, did they kind of avoid you?
No, my friends didn't.
They were more curious and pleased with my question.
And talked about it.
It's something I never just refused to talk about.
I think I told my brother one time, like, talk about something else.
I kind of got burned out on them.
But it seems like everybody that's asked me questions, everybody wants to talk about me sincerely.
They made me think they wanted to know something, so I was always willing to talk to them about it.
But I don't know what my life would have been like
If I hadn't have done it, I would.
The things I did and didn't do after I got back was pretty wild when I got back.
I just was, you know, kind of a rebel type of thing.
Nobody would tell me what to do.
I know that A&M will have more time.
history class.
History is one of the biggest .
But at the time, I just, you know, I'm sitting here thinking, you know, well, I've already, I've been on the other side of the world.
I've been through all this.
I don't have to sit here and listen to this and shake your head here.
I've been out of the classroom, and this is 23 years.
It helped me.
And I was like, well, I just got in more trouble.
I know that didn't help me in anything.
That was just the way I felt.
And any time you ran into a veteran that's been over there, you made friends with them.
That's who you're most associated with.
So you're not into a little more coping?
Like, a lot of people come back and, I mean, they're really scarred.
I mean, they get all of a sudden, they're bitter.
I mean, you're not bitter.
Are you bitter?
No.
I was reading an author.
I might have been in this last reader's project, but...
Not everybody goes out to it.
Like the Platoon movie?
They went to go see a movie with Jane Fonda.
Yeah.
And they went outside in the lobby and they were just all crying.
Yeah, I went to see Platoon.
I didn't go out to the lobby.
I don't know.
I think I got a little drunk on two or three scenes.
It didn't bother me.
The only thing that I had to adjust to was
sleeping when I got back.
It was hard to know that you could, and it only lasted for like a week or two.
I was afraid to go to sleep.
I was afraid I wouldn't wake up, you know, but I couldn't convince myself I was safe in the climate of my room.
Because over there, that's one thing you did go to sleep on.
So yeah, I didn't sleep then.
I don't know.
It's not a twig, it wasn't a rifle.
Thunder came over the other hand.
And that and a sudden, but anymore, a sudden rifle or pistol shot just about hit me on the ground.
But it took about over a year to get it back.
I got back in November.
Pistols coming on, firetruckers.
You know, sometimes I thought I was going to have a heart attack just driving down the street.
And still to this day, a gunshot that goes off without me knowing what it's fixing to do, I really get up.
It had a pretty good impact, I guess on my life.
Ever since I was a little kid, I wanted a plate army a lot.
Say it's fulfilling a kid's dream to go to war, but it was an experience that I wouldn't take for...
I wouldn't really want to go to war, but I wouldn't trade it for anything.
How did you feel about the anti-war protesters?
Those people, I don't really have a whole lot of interest in them.
uh uh the people that
were in school that, uh, you're smart enough to stay in school, they, uh, I, I remember correctly, you know, they just didn't pull you out of school.
If you chose to go to school, you could walk out of school.
Uh, married and so many kids, I think, and I don't exactly know how much.
Uh, but the ones that, uh, deliberately, gods left the craft where they deliberately
I tried to stay out of the distance before they took me out the other day.
I didn't have much use for them.
I mean, back to the station.
What about vets that have come back from Vietnam and now they're against it?
We had some people come and talk to us.
They were from veterans for peace and veterans against the war.
And they think the world is totally wrong now.
And they speak out against it.
And if they've been over there and they came back, do you think they're not bitter toward it?
No.
I couldn't be.
I'd say if there's any bitterness, it's at war.
I'm not even sure if Lyndon Johnson had control over it, but somebody did, but more than one person did.
Whoever those people were, I have no bitterness for the harm of the military.
Even though we didn't accomplish what the G.I.
wanted us to accomplish, we had to do some good at the time.
The Vietnamese that are in America today, if we hadn't have done it, they wouldn't be here today.
A lot of lives were changed.
I mean, I'm kind of, I don't know how I feel about, you know, the business coming over here now.
They're taking jobs, you know, but their lives are so much better now than they were before.
They're, they're just like, they're, you know, they're just looking for a better way of living.
Nobody that lives here in the United States really has any idea of what communism really is, except for what you read.
You go into a country that is, it would be the last thing you would want in your country.
So even though that, you know,
They took it all over.
I don't know just what I'm trying to say.
I just wish there'd been less.
I would like to see Vietnam today, a democratic society.
It's a beautiful country, and the people are great.
I hope someday I can go back to Vietnam and do this and this.
Yeah.
Oh, yeah.
I don't know.
It's just kind of like the air going out of the boom, I guess.
It's not like, you know, it was all for nothing.
No, it was for something.
I don't really know what, but it was.
But it was kind of sad to see it go down.
You didn't have to do that.
Let it go, I guess.
The movies, there's been a lot of push for movies in Vietnam and all this stuff lately.
Do you think most of that's an adequate portrayal of what happened over there?
Somewhere they all have some authenticity to it.
I've seen 14 in a full metal jacket.
There's just, most of it's made from the entertainment.
But you can, I don't know, some of it's got some brain to it, but the majority of it's not made from it.
When we were measuring progress, do you think progress could be measured over there when you were fighting?
Because they use body counts and various things like that.
Do you think there was really an adequate way to measure progress over there?
As far as the body count, how you were...
I mean, we've had a lot of multiple fights and... Yeah, I think there was a lot of stretching and shooting there.
The company commander can call in a body count.
He may not have one, but he just may have an estimation of what.
A lot of times you can see how many he did.
Or they may just say, well, there's a freighter over here that had to be two or three, and that might have had them before he got stressed out.
I don't know.
It's a...
There was a lot of, we have found, we have made enough of it, and it killed a lot of people.
We've got members, hundreds and hundreds and hundreds of thousands of people over there.
As far as the actual number, there is a number that we've claimed they killed.
Thank you.
We have probably more than we have to do.
I don't think so.
Not where we were anyway.
Maybe there was up north.
I have no idea.
